Summary of bugs fixed during development
-----------------------------------------

1. coffea AccumulatorABC incompatibility
   Problem : hist.Hist (from the 'hist' package) is not a subclass of
             coffea's AccumulatorABC. dict_accumulator.add() raises
             ValueError when it encounters a new key whose value is
             not AccumulatorABC (it cannot call .identity() on it).
   Fix     : Replaced dict_accumulator + hist.Hist with column_accumulator
             (a native coffea type that concatenates numpy arrays).
             Histograms and ROC are now computed in post-processing
             from the concatenated score/weight arrays.

2. mplhep.cms.label wrong keyword argument
   Problem : mplhep.cms.label() in this environment does not accept
             'energy' as a keyword; raises TypeError.
   Fix     : Changed 'energy=13.6' to 'com=13.6'.

3. ROC denominator used abs() while numerator did not
   Problem : compute_roc() used np.sum(np.abs(hist)) as the denominator
             but np.cumsum(hist) (unsigned) as the numerator.
             For NLO samples with ~21% negative genWeights, the histogram
             bins can be negative in some score ranges, making the efficiency
             at threshold=0 come out to ~0.58 instead of 1.0, which
             corrupts the AUC integral.
   Fix     : Changed denominator to np.sum(weights) (net signed sum).
             Also added a filter to drop events with score < 0
             (fill_none sentinel for jets where probT + probQCD = 0).

4. Raw genWeights differ across Zto2Nu pT-slices by orders of magnitude
   Problem : Zto2Nu is split into ~10 pT-slice datasets.
             The raw genWeight within amcatnloFXFX NLO samples has
             different absolute scales per pT-slice. When all slices
             are concatenated with raw genWeights, high-pT slices
             (large |genWeight|) dominate the ROC histogram, giving
             a distorted efficiency curve and AUC << 0.5.
   Fix     : Weight each event by sign(genWeight) instead of the raw
             genWeight. This gives each event a weight of +1 or -1,
             treating all pT-slices equally while still correctly
             cancelling NLO negative-weight events within each sample.


Note on AUC = 0.09 (expected physics, not a bug)
--------------------------------------------------
At WP = 0.26: sig eff = 47%, bkg eff = 0.94% (106x rejection).
The tagger discriminates well AT the working point.

AUC < 0.5 occurs because the remaining 53% of signal events (where
the top is not boosted or decays semi-leptonically) land at low
TvsQCD alongside the 99% of Zto2Nu events. The ROC drops below the
diagonal for most of the x-axis range, pulling AUC below 0.5.

This is expected for INCLUSIVE samples without signal-region selection.
The toptagging_guide.md specifies "derive ROC in signal region": adding
MET > 200 GeV and zero-lepton veto would remove non-boosted-top events
and restore AUC > 0.5.

genWeight statistics (1 file per dataset):
  Zto2Nu: 21.7% negative weights, sum = 2.24e+07
  Signal: 20.7% negative weights, sum = 4.51e+02


RuntimeWarning notes
---------------------
"invalid value encountered in divide" warnings during processing are
harmless. They come from TvsQCD = probT / (probT + probQCD) when
probT + probQCD = 0 for a small number of jets. These are caught by
ak.fill_none(..., -1.) and filtered out in compute_roc (score < 0 mask).


Why the ROC plot shows two diagonal lines (bkg_eff x-axis)
-----------------------------------------------------------
The two near-parallel diagonal lines are the dashed Random reference (y=x)
and the solid ROC curve itself. They run almost on top of each other for
bkg_eff > ~0.05 because the signal sample is fully inclusive and contains
two populations:

  Boosted tops (~50%): top fully merged into the AK15 jet -> high TvsQCD
    -> tagger correctly prefers signal -> ROC rises above the diagonal
    -> visible as the sharp spike in the upper-left corner

  Non-boosted tops (~50%): top not merged, or semi-leptonic decay
    -> the AK15 jet captures only ISR QCD radiation -> low TvsQCD
    -> looks identical to Zto2Nu's ISR jets -> ROC follows the diagonal

Zto2Nu has no hadronic top: its leading AK15 jet is always ISR QCD
-> also low TvsQCD. So both non-boosted signal and Zto2Nu background
are indistinguishable to the tagger in the loose-cut region.

The ROC is very slightly BELOW the diagonal in that region (mildly
anti-discriminating), so the area lost below cancels most of the area
gained in the upper-left corner, giving AUC ~ 0.10 instead of 0.5.

Fix: apply signal-region cuts before computing the ROC:
  - MET > 200 GeV
  - zero-lepton veto
  (optionally: fat jet pT cut)
These remove most non-boosted-top events, restoring AUC > 0.5 and
eliminating the second diagonal line.


Full-dataset run with signal-region cuts (2022pre, 1002 files, 60 workers)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Run command:
  python roc_curve.py \
      --metadata decaf/analysis/metadata/2022_private_v2.json.gz \
      --year 2022pre --workers 60 \
      --save-arrays hists/roc_arrays_2022pre_sr.coffea --output plots/

Selections applied:
  AK15 jet : pT > 160 GeV, |eta| < 2.4, tight+tightLepVeto (jetId & 6 == 6)
  Leading  : pT > 250 GeV
  MET      : pT > 350 GeV
  Lepton   : 0 loose e (pT>10, cutBased>=1), 0 loose mu (pT>10, looseId+iso),
             0 loose pho (pT>20, cutBased>=1, electronVeto)
  b-jet    : 0 PNet-loose b-tagged AK4 (pT>30) with dR > 1.5 from leading AK15
             PNet loose WPs: 2022pre=0.047, 2022post=0.0499,
                             2023pre=0.0358, 2023post=0.0359

Results:
  Signal events passing presel:     5,422
  Background events passing presel: 2,070,490
  AUC = 0.0485

  Target e_bkg  Actual e_bkg  Threshold  e_sig   Rejection
